<% begin_sec("The gamma factor",nil,'gamma') %>\index{gamma factor!defined}

Figure \figref{twin-paradox} is the relativistic version of example \ref{eg:galilean-twin-paradox}
on p.~\pageref{eg:galilean-twin-paradox}.\index{twin paradox}
We intend to analyze it using the metric, and since the
metric gives the same result in any frame, we have chosen for convenience to represent it in the
frame in which the earth is at rest. 
We have $\vc{a}=(t,0)$ and $\vc{b}=(t,vx)$, where $v$ is the velocity of the spaceship relative
to the earth. Application of the metric gives proper time $t$ for the earthbound twin
and $t\sqrt{1-v^2}$ for the traveling twin. The same results apply for $\vc{c}$ and $\vc{d}$. The result
is that the earthbound twin experiences a time that is greater by a factor $\gamma$ (Greek letter gamma)
defined as $\gamma=1/\sqrt{1-v^2}$. If $v$ is close to $c$, $\gamma$ can be large, and we find that when
the astronaut twin returns home, still youthful, the earthbound twin can be old and gray. This was at one
time referred to as the twin paradox, and it was considered paradoxical either because it seemed to defy
common sense or because the traveling twin could argue that she was the one at rest while the earth was
moving. The violation of common sense
is in fact what was observed in the Hafele-Keating experiment, and the latter
argument is fallacious for the same reasons as in the 
Galilean version given in example \ref{eg:galilean-twin-paradox}.
